message:
No, I would not use ContinueWith here.

Your existing code swallows exceptions - which I do not generally do. Also, there's a Task.Run wrapper around an async method, which is quite odd and merits investigation. But if you want to keep both these behaviors, you could do:

public override void DoViewReadyCommand()  
{  
base.DoViewReadyCommand();

DoViewReadyCommandAsync();  
}

private async Task DoViewReadyCommandAsync()  
{  
var result = await Task.Run(async () =>  
{  
var accountManager = ManagerLocator.GetAccountsManager();  
return await accountManager.GetEmailAccountsAsync();  
});  
SetRegisteredEmailAccountViewModels(result);  
}

On a side note, why not use async void for DoViewReadyCommand?

Hi Stephen,   
 I am working on a Xamarin application. Inside a viewmodel:  
```  
public override void DoViewReadyCommand()  
 {  
 base.DoViewReadyCommand();

 Task.Run(async () =>  
 {  
 var accountManager = ManagerLocator.GetAccountsManager();  
 return await accountManager.GetEmailAccountsAsync();  
 }).ContinueWith((t) => SetRegisteredEmailAccountViewModels(t.Result),   
 CancellationToken.None,   
 TaskContinuationOptions.OnlyOnRanToCompletion,   
 TaskScheduler.FromCurrentSynchronizationContext());  
}  
```  
Is here the use of a the continuation task valid?   
You do not recommend using ContinueWith. Is there any way, without declaring the DoViewReadyCommand to async void nor using ContinueWith, to implement the same logic?
